# Client / Server Module Boundary

## The rule

Files with `"use client"` must **never** import runtime values from server modules.

Server modules are any file that uses:
- `import "server-only"`
- `prisma` / `@/lib/prisma`
- `node:fs`, `fs`, database queries, or other Node-only APIs

## Safe in client components

```typescript
import type { PlayerProfile } from "@/lib/player-profile-types";
import { periodKeyForDate } from "@/lib/player-profile-analytics";
```

## Unsafe (causes `node:fs` / Webpack build errors)

```typescript
import { getPlayerProfileBySlug, periodKeyForDate } from "@/lib/player-profile";
import type { PlayerProfile } from "@/lib/player-profile"; // still resolves server module in some bundlers
```

Even `import type` from `player-profile.ts` can pull the server graph in dev. Use **`player-profile-types.ts`** for all client type imports.

## Where to put shared logic

| Layer | Path pattern | Use for |
|-------|----------------|---------|
| Client-safe types | `src/lib/player-profile-types.ts` | All `PlayerProfile` types in `"use client"` files |
| Client-safe helpers | `src/lib/player-profile-analytics.ts` | Pure functions for charts |
| Server-only | `src/lib/player-profile.ts` | `getPlayerProfileBySlug()`, Prisma loaders |

When a helper is needed in both server and client, extract it to a **client-safe** module with zero server imports. Server files may import from client-safe modules.

## Guardrail

Add `import "server-only";` at the top of every file that touches Prisma or the database. Next.js will fail fast with a clear error instead of an obscure `node:fs` Webpack error.
